MAS8954 Practical Solutions: PCA on the Sphere

Tom Nye

Autumn 2023

This build of rgl does not include OpenGL functions.  Use
 rglwidget() to display results, e.g. via options(rgl.printRglwidget = TRUE).

Start by reading in the data:

> sphdataA = as.matrix(read.csv(file="sphdataA.txt",header=FALSE))
> sphdataB = as.matrix(read.csv(file="sphdataB.txt",header=FALSE))

Question 1 Plot data set A:

> plot_spherical_data(sphdataA)
> rglwidget()

Data set A forms a widely spread spot, with some points falling outside the hemisphere which contains the main concentration of data. The pattern is roughly rotationally symmetric through the centre of the spot.

Plot data set B:

> close3d()
> plot_spherical_data(sphdataB, col=2)
> rglwidget()

Data set B is narrower in one direction than the other and it forms an elongated or elliptical spot across the surface of the sphere.

Question 2

Calculate means in the chordal metric.

> muA = sphere.chordal.mean(sphdataA)
> muB = sphere.chordal.mean(sphdataB)
> 
> muApol = cartesian.to.polar3d(muA)
> muBpol = cartesian.to.polar3d(muB)
> # Theta and phi for mean of data set A:
> muApol[2:3]*180/pi
      V2       V3 
29.58247 44.36205 
> # Theta and phi for mean of data set B:
> muBpol[2:3]*180/pi
      V2       V3 
28.54184 45.40317

The data sets have almost exactly the same means.

Calculate variances in the chordal metric.

> (sphere.chordal.variance(sphdataA))
[1] 0.2824729
> (sphere.chordal.variance(sphdataB))
[1] 0.3161447

Their variances are also similar. Variance lies between 0 (concentrated) and 2 (highly dispersed). The values around 0.3 indicate fairly concentrated data.

Try adding the mean, e.g. to the plot of data set B.

> close3d()
> plot_spherical_data(sphdataB, col=1)
> plot_spherical_data(t(muB), add=TRUE, col=2, size = 1.5)
> rglwidget()

Question 3

Both data sets have a few points on the opposite hemisphere to the mean. However, overall the level of distortion in the projections will be fairly small, since the variances are small. The points in data set A do not have a preferred direction around the mean point, and so the first principal component will not approximate the data well. In contrast, the points in data set B have a direction from the mean in which there is more variation: the principal component will point in this direction and be a better approximation to the data.

Question 4

Tangent PCA for data set A:

> tangentdataA = tangent_projection(sphdataA, muA)
> close3d()
> plot_spherical_data(sphdataA)
> plot_spherical_data(tangentdataA, add=TRUE, col=2, size=0.5)
> tangent.PCA(tangentdataA, muA)
Sum of perpendicular distances =  26.525 
Total sum of squared distances =  59.863 
Ratio =  0.4430939 
Proportion of variance (1-ratio) =  0.5569061 
> rglwidget()

For data set B:

> tangentdataB = tangent_projection(sphdataB, muA)
> close3d()
> plot_spherical_data(sphdataB)
> plot_spherical_data(tangentdataB, add=TRUE, col=2, size=0.5)
> tangent.PCA(tangentdataB, muB)
Sum of perpendicular distances =  12.732 
Total sum of squared distances =  66.664 
Ratio =  0.1909803 
Proportion of variance (1-ratio) =  0.8090197 
> rglwidget()

The ratio of perpendicular squared distances to the total squared distances is smaller for data set B than for A. In other words, the line corresponding to the principal component is a better approximation to the data than for data set A. The proportion of variance explained by the principal component is 80% for data set B, whereas it is 55% for data set A. (The minimum possible for 2D data is 50%). The principal component identifies the direction of maximum spread in data set B. In data set A, the principal component is a poor fit to the data: almost any other direction through the mean would be as good.
